📝 A → B (Easy) — How to Think
🔹 Step 1: Ignore Simulation

First instinct might be: “try flips, track cost…” ❌
But here, operations are too flexible → answer is always small (0 or 1).

So think in terms of properties of the string, not operations.

🔹 Step 2: What makes cost = 0 possible?

Cost 0 happens when:

A[L] ≠ A[R]

👉 This means:

You need at least one '0' and one '1' in the string
Then you can always pick endpoints smartly and flip for free

💡 So:

If string has both 0 & 1 → you have full control (free operations)

🔹 Step 3: When do you get stuck?

You get stuck when string is:

00000  OR  11111

👉 Why?

Any segment you pick → endpoints are same
So every flip costs 1

💡 So:

Uniform string = no free moves = forced cost 1

🔹 Step 4: Apply this to A → B

Now think carefully:

Case 1: Already equal
A == B → cost = 0
Case 2: A has both 0 & 1 AND B has both
You have freedom in A
Target B is also flexible

👉 You can adjust bits using only cost 0 flips

Answer = 0
Case 3: Either A or B is uniform
If A is uniform → you can't start with free moves
If B is uniform → final step forces same endpoints

👉 In both situations, at least one paid move is unavoidable

Answer = 1
🔹 Final Mental Model (Very Important)

Think like this in contest:

“Do I have both 0 and 1 available to freely manipulate?”

YES (in both A & B) → 0
NO (any one is uniform) → 1
🔹 Clean Code Template
void solve() {
    int n; string a, b;
    cin >> n >> a >> b;

    if (a == b) {
        cout << 0 << endl;
        return;
    }

    bool all_a = true, all_b = true;

    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        if (a[i] != a[0]) all_a = false;
        if (b[i] != b[0]) all_b = false;
    }

    cout << (all_a || all_b ? 1 : 0) << endl;
}
⚡ One-line intuition

Variety (0 & 1) = freedom → cost 0
No variety = restriction → cost 1
